Sub-additive 3D printing\nis a fundamental deviation
from the standard process\nof 3D printing, which
is a horizontal deposition of\ntwo paths layer upon layer.
And we showed that in the\nvarious other projects prior.
For certain complex geometries,\nlike shells, this method
has severe disadvantages.
Depositing cementitious material\non a supportive aggregate
is not a new thing.
The Philips Pavilion at\nthe Brussels Expo '58
was one of the first\nmodern examples
to panelize a large complex\nsurface through land forming.
So casting on a shaped\nhyperbolic sand form,
multiple panels were\nproduced as sections
