So Log Knot is a\nproject that emerged
from our first initial\nexploration with custom
wood-based tools for the\nrobot that Leslie just showed.
And wood is an\ninteresting material
because it surrounds\nus in so many ways.
As a building material,\nwe encounter wood
in the shape of two\nby fours or plywood
or other standardized\ndimensions.
But as this image shows,\nwood comes from trees
that are usually non-standard.
Log Knot is a\nrobotically fabricated
architectural installation which\naims to expand and optimize
the use of entire trees\nand irregular timber
geometries and construction.
The research team, which\nincluded Brian Havener,
a research associate, who did\nthis project in his M.Arch
studio, and then continued\nto work on it as a research
associate in the lab.
The team examined\nwhether regular--
irregular roundwood\ngeometries can
be processed to construct\ncompound curvature assemblies.
The project creates\nan infinite loop
of roundwood curving three\ndimensionally along its length.
And the project\nborrowed strategies
from traditional wood\nbuilding and manufacturing
while implementing\ncontemporary technologies
to achieve precision\nand mass customization.
Components are\ncomputationally processed
to form a spatially\ncomplex figure eight knot.
This is a series of\ndiagrams and studies
and a conceptual\nmodel on the site.
In a reciprocal design\nprocess, the project
fosters synergies and feedback\nbetween material fabrication,
digital form, and full\nscale construction.
New technological\nparadigms, such as
robotic-based fabrication,\nradically challenge
our understanding of wood\nas a building material,
but have yet to take\nbetter advantage of wood
as a sustainable and smart\nmaterial for construction.
Small roundwood members or tree\nforks are usually not utilized
for construction purposes\nbecause today sawmills are not
equipped to process those\nirregular tree geometries.
So this project uses\ncomputation to optimize
each joint for tension forces.
And each of the\njoints is precisely
rotated to resist forces\nand local buckling.
Here you see a detail of the\nvarious mortise and tendon
joints that we tested\nfor the project.
Each joint is secured\nby three lag bolts.
And Log Knot is designed\nfor disassembly,
therefore relying upon the\nuse of steel lag bolts instead
of wooden dowels.
The fabrication was done\non our Kuka platform
using a custom CNC\nmill and effector.
The mill first creates a\nplanar surface on the log,
and then creates the mortise\nand tendon rough cut.
We then use the\nside of the end mill
to smoothen the rough cut,\nwhich saves a lot of time,
and is an efficient way of\nutilizing the tool that we have
at hand and the end effector.
And to prevent\nchecking and shaking,
the milled end grains were\ncovered in pentacryl, which
is a non-toxic wood stabilizer.
And so this prevented\nchecking, and allowed
us to assemble these pieces\nmore or less accurately.
As we worked with\nsmall budgets, we
did not have access\nto heavy machinery,
and therefore developed a\nself-sufficient construction
method that requires only\nminimal form work or support.
So the idea was, can\nwe design a joint
that is so smart that it guides\nthe shape and form of the wood
assembly?
So each component was\nlifted and placed by hand.
And while we think\nconcrete is heavy,
wood is also surprisingly\nheavy in these dimensions.
So this is a\nconsiderable effort.
And then in the second step,\nwe fastened the wood in place
using the geometry of the joint\nto guide the form of the arc.
So here you see a video\nof the assembly process.
And so to hold up the\nstructure during construction,
all that is required is a\nminimal support of attached two
by fours.
So you see them emerging at\nthe top of the frame, the two
two-by-fours nailed\nto the wood structure
to give some additional support.
Unfamiliar notions of\ncraftsmanship and precision,
both digital and analog,\nemerged from Log Knot's
conceptual design practice and\ncharacteristic construction
technique.
Log Knot was exhibited as part\nof Cornell's 2018 Biennial
called "Duration--
Passage, Persistent, Survival,"\nand addresses this theme
on multiple levels.
Environmental cycles,\nbirth, growth, and decay
are intrinsic to complex forest\necosystems and processes.
Conceptually and spatially,\nthe Log Knot project
references these internal cycles\nand reciprocal relationships
between systems, both\nnatural and technical.
The infinite looping\nstructure is an interplay
between archaic natural\ngeometry, advanced computation,
and state of the art\ndigital fabrication.
By questioning how forests\nare used as a resource,
Log Knot provides a\ncritical commentary
on various perpetual\nwood cycles--
economic, environmental,\nand cultural in nature.
From the ground up, new material\nmeans and construction methods
are intrinsic to the making\nof this last project.
The Ashen Cabin\nrecalibrates expectations
around digital\nfabrication methods,
and out of contextual\nnecessity explores
the architectural opportunities\nof digital-analog construction
hybrids from the ground up\nto the scale of the building.
And informed by multiple\nforces, the building
follows two strands of\nmaterial narratives.
It is 3D printed from\nconcrete and clothed
in a robotically fabricated\nenvelope constructed
from irregular wood logs.
The making of the\nbuilding is also
informed by the key\nenvironmental crisis
of the ash trees\nin North America.
Since its discovery\nin the US in 2002,
the emerald ash borer killed\ntens of millions of ash trees,
drastically transforming\nthe entire forest ecosystems
in the process.
The EAB threatens to\neradicate nearly all
of the 8.7 billion ash\ntrees in North America.
And as of October 2018,\nit is found in 35 states
and several Canadian provinces.
As a reference, 10% of all\ntrees in New York state
are ash trees.
So that is almost 1 in 10 trees\nyou see will die or are dying.
And this is a huge problem.
And our means of\nconstruction might
contribute to some form of\ngruesome, after-the-effect
remedy.
